(373059, 11553, 372141, 'Fudgepacker', 15152, '', 1372200791, '[QUOTE=Aquarius;372141]Ah polymers.. everywhere the problem arises with the polymers.\nBTW polymer frame kabooms are not uncommon.[/QUOTE]\nKb''s have absolutely nothing to do with polymer frames, they occur in the chamber. The frame is considered a low stress component. "Frame bulge" on CZ''s is strictly a cosmetic issue, with no effect on durability, reliability, nor accuracy. Ruger even uses all polymer frame rails on their P345 (in 45ACP!), and Beretta uses a polymer striker in their CX4. The locking block, slide, barrel, chamber, are the parts that are exposed to high impact, high pressure, high stress, and are thus always made out of steel. Even in metal Sigs, the frame is aluminum and the upper is steel. If the technology was available 100 years ago, all pistols would have had plastic frames for its advantages in low weight, ease of production, economy, and durability. That''s why the new models from HK, CZ, Glock, S&W, Sig, Caracal, FN, Keltec, Ruger, SA, and Beretta... are all polymer framed. Dont know if I like it, but RIA even makes a polymer framed 1911.', 1, 0, '24.85.141.11', 0, 1, 0, 0, 0, 'on_nl2br', 0, 0),
